John Edward: Language skills are essential for world citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain an academic excellence path that continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is reinforced with individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With over 30,000 students all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), are working to offer a service of the best level to students and parents.
The goal of independent schools is to prepare students for further and higher education, for their careers and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a custom school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a very popular and desirable choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak a man in a language you understand, you’ll get to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart."
This is a very important reminder that we cannot depend only on English if we want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of the exams of this year, we can see that languages lead the classification tables with the highest qualifications in independent schools.
68% of the students who studied foreign languages obtained the highest grade A.
Data, compiled from 74 SCIS schools, reflected that 72% of students obtained A superior qualification in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students, and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital competences that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Today, languages, as a subject of choice, are kept in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools and in other places.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the United Kingdom Employment and Competence Commission revealed that 17% of the reasons employers gave for filling their vacancies were attributed to a lack of language skills.
So language skills are increasingly needed to prepare young people for their future careers.
As there are more and more potential job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of a person’s choice of career, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such a permanent competence.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of competition.
According to a survey conducted in 2013 by YouGov among more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and the French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double digit percentage.
So investing in language teaching is important to children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find important work.
There is diversity between schools in Scotland in terms of languages taught.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be more important for the United Kingdom in the future, by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your son's interest is, he'll always be able to choose between a series of languages in independent schools, which have staff teaching specialists in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and provide them with the necessary skills to succeed, regardless of what the future may bring.
In today's global trading environment, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as “international communicative competences”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence to Scottish young people.
We have to do this right.
