Harvard Students Course on Rest Habits · Global Voices
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the growing culture of studying all night, stimulated by caffeine.
One scholar observed that university students number one in the world are often left out on the basics about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of Sound Medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of his species in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
"At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, "Why are you telling me now, all this, in my last year?"
He said that no one had ever talked to him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he reported to The Telegraph.
In the course, implemented for the first time this year, students are told the basic concepts about how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, in addition to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Executive Director of Health Services at the University, stated that the University decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a dorm, where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, bamboos and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how sports performance affects sleeplessness, and the importance of keeping a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that students’ conduct will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes," said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride of staying awake all night still exists, he said, and added that modern technology and growing pressure suffered by students make sleep deprivation an increasing problem.
Making sure to enjoy a sound of good quality for long enough should be a "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, tiredness and anxiety, added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into inanition mode and makes students always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of Physics Chemistry and Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes in the last year of his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he expects, is to ask postgraduate students to conduct a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students take into account the fact that they should be alarmed when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emit electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
