Red Tide Update: Concentrations Reduce to Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission's latest report shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more widespread proliferation conditions are being reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier areas, suggesting a lower concentration.
The proliferation of the red tide extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee Counties.
Spots can be found 16 km from the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places, compared to last week's situation.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations have been reported at the coast or at a distance from the coast to Pinellas County over the past week, low concentrations at high altitudes away from the coast to Hillsborough County, background or high concentrations at Manatee County, background concentrations at medium to Charlotte County, high-level concentrations at the coast or away from Lee County Coast and low concentrations at Collier County County.
Respiratory irritations continue to occur in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeast Florida.
